<P>
The following fundamental lemma of this section is easy to prove now.

<P>
<P>
<DIV><A NAME="duales_Komplement"><B>Lemma  3.1</B></A> &nbsp; 
We have <!-- MATH
 ${K(A)}^{\bot} ={\rm Ev}_{{\cal E}}(C(A))$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="177" HEIGHT="45" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img68.png"
 ALT="${K(A)}^{\bot} ={\rm Ev}_{{\cal E}}(C(A))$"> and
<!-- MATH
 ${{K(A)}^{\bot}}^{\bot} ={\rm Ev}_{{{\cal E}}^*}({C(A)}^{\bot})$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="206" HEIGHT="53" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img69.png"
 ALT="${{K(A)}^{\bot}}^{\bot} ={\rm Ev}_{{{\cal E}}^*}({C(A)}^{\bot})$"></DIV><P></P>

<P>
P<SMALL>ROOF: </SMALL>According to the definition <!-- MATH
 ${\rm Ev}_{{\cal E}}(b)\in {K(A)}^{\bot}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="140" HEIGHT="45" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img70.png"
 ALT="${\rm Ev}_{{\cal E}}(b)\in {K(A)}^{\bot}$"> if and only if
<!-- MATH
 ${\rm Ev}_{{\cal E}}(b)({\vartheta}_{tr}([x,a]))={\vartheta}_{tr}([x,a])(b)=0$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="310" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img71.png"
 ALT="${\rm Ev}_{{\cal E}}(b)({\vartheta}_{tr}([x,a]))={\vartheta}_{tr}([x,a])(b)=0$"> for all <!-- MATH
 $x \in {\cal E}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img72.png"
 ALT="$x \in {\cal E}$">
and <IMG
 WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img73.png"
 ALT="$a\in A$">. Applying (<A HREF="node3.html#Lieklammer">4</A>) this is the case if and only if
<IMG
 WIDTH="76" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img74.png"
 ALT="$[a,b]=0$"> for all <IMG
 WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img73.png"
 ALT="$a\in A$">, thus if and only if
<IMG
 WIDTH="79" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img75.png"
 ALT="$b \in C(A)$">. The second equation follows from the first by use of
equation (<A HREF="node3.html#Ev_comp">3</A>).<IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img35.png"
 ALT="$\Box$">
<BR><P>
Remember that the dual module
<!-- MATH
 ${C}^*={\rm Hom}_{R}{(C,R)}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="153" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img76.png"
 ALT="${C}^*={\rm Hom}_{R}{(C,R)}$"> of a coalgebra <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img36.png"
 ALT="$C$"> always posseses the structure
of an algebra by use of the <EM>convolution product</EM> 

<P>
<BR><P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
\mu \nu :=(\mu \otimes \nu) \circ\Delta \;\;\mbox{ where }
\mu ,\nu \in {C}^*.
\end{displaymath}
 -->

<IMG
 WIDTH="427" HEIGHT="33" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img77.png"
 ALT="\begin{displaymath}\mu \nu :=(\mu \otimes \nu) \circ\Delta \;\;\mbox{ where }
\mu ,\nu \in {C}^*.
\end{displaymath}">
</DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL">
<P></P>

<P>
Here, we have identified <!-- MATH
 $\mu \otimes \nu$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img78.png"
 ALT="$\mu \otimes \nu$"> with its image under the
natural homomorphism
<!-- MATH
 ${C}^* \otimes {C}^* \rightarrow {(C \otimes C)}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="177" HEIGHT="39" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img79.png"
 ALT="${C}^* \otimes {C}^* \rightarrow {(C \otimes C)}^*$">. Note that this 
construction is functorial. In the special case
<!-- MATH
 $C={{\cal E}}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="64" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img80.png"
 ALT="$C={{\cal E}}^*$"> we obtain an algebra structure on <!-- MATH
 ${{{\cal E}}^*}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="19" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img81.png"
 ALT="${{{\cal E}}^*}^*$">. Furthermore
it is easy to show that the evaluation map
<!-- MATH
 ${\rm Ev}_{{\cal E}}:{\cal E}\rightarrow {{{\cal E}}^*}^*$
 -->
