<P>
At the beginning of this section we have constructed an algebra
structure on the dual module of a coalgebra. Conversely we should obtain
a coalgebra structure on the dual of an algebra <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img24.png"
 ALT="$A$">. Whereas this is not
possible in general, it can be done under certain restrictions to
the <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">-module structure of the algebra <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img24.png"
 ALT="$A$">. To be more precise,
the natural <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">-homomorphism from <!-- MATH
 ${A}^*\otimes {A}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="71" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img105.png"
 ALT="${A}^*\otimes {A}^*$"> into
<!-- MATH
 ${(A\otimes A)}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="39" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img106.png"
 ALT="${(A\otimes A)}^*$"> must be an isomorphism. This is the case
if <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img24.png"
 ALT="$A$"> is projective and finitely generated. Therefore, under these
circumstances the construction is always possible and functorial,
that is: duals of algebra maps become coalgebra maps. Thus we obtain

<P>
<P>
<DIV><A NAME="duale_Koalgebra"><B>Theorem  3.7</B></A> (Second Comparison Theorem)  &nbsp; 
Suppose the centralizer algebra <IMG
 WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img91.png"
 ALT="$C(A)$"> of <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img24.png"
 ALT="$A$"> is a direct summand in
<IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img9.png"
 ALT="${\cal E}$"> as an <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">-module. Then
<IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="39" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img107.png"
 ALT="${C(A)}^*$"> can be turned into a coalgebra. The map 
<!-- MATH
 $\theta:M(A)\rightarrow {C(A)}^*$
